NAME: Fund
DESCRIPTION: Investment fund shares are shares of an investment fund if the fund has a corporate structure. They are known as units if the fund is a trust. Investment funds are collective investment undertakings through which investors pool funds for investment in financial and/or non-financial assets. Funds are part of the financial assets and liabilities (financial instrument) category “equity and investment fund shares or units” (F.5) and belong to the subcategory “Investment fund shares or units” (F.52) in ESA 2010.

NAME: Equity
DESCRIPTION: Equity securities are negotiable financial instruments that entitle holders to a share of both distributed profits and the residual value of the corporation’s assets in the event of its liquidation. Holders of these financial assets are the collective owners of a corporation. Equity securities are part of the financial assets and liabilities (financial instrument) category “equity and investment fund shares or units” (F.5) and belong to the subcategory “equity” (F.51) in ESA 2010.

NAME: Debt
DESCRIPTION: Debt securities are negotiable financial instruments serving as evidence of a debt. They are covered by the financial assets and liabilities (financial instrument) category “debt securities” (F.3) in ESA 2010.

NAME: Ordinary / Common share
DESCRIPTION:
Ordinary shares (or “common” shares) usually give holders the right to the following:
• Holders are generally entitled to participate in the corporation’s general policymaking and have the right to attend, speak, and vote (in the case of voting shares) at general meetings. Holders of ordinary shares can vote on corporate objectives and matters of policy, on stock splits, and to elect the corporation’s board of directors.
• Holders are usually entitled to a preferential subscription in the event of a capital increase. Some holders of ordinary shares also receive preemptive rights (a rights issue), which enables them to retain their proportional share in the ownership
of a corporation should it issue more stock.
• Holders generally have the right to a share in the corporation’s profits. However, no fixed dividends are paid out to ordinary shareholders. Ordinary shareholders’ returns are therefore uncertain and dependent on earnings, corporate reinvestment, and the market’s ability to value and sell stock efficiently.

NAME: Bond
DESCRIPTION: Bonds and debentures are long-term debt securities that give the holders the unconditional right to fixed payments or contractually determined variable payments on a specified date or dates, that is, the earning of interest is not dependent on earnings of the debtors. Bonds and debentures also give holders the unconditional right to fixed sums as payments to the creditor on a specified date or dates.

NAME: Other equity
DESCRIPTION: An equity instrument that is of a type not listed separately. This also includes "Other equity" in accordance with ESA 2010 (F.519) that is not in the form of securities. Other equity includes equity in quasi-corporations (such as branches, trusts, and partnerships), as well as notional units representing ownership of real estate.

NAME: Other debt
DESCRIPTION: A debt instrument that is of a type not listed separately.

NAME: Other fund
DESCRIPTION: A fund that is of a type not listed separately.

NAME: Subscription right
DESCRIPTION: Subscription rights that are traded separately are often given their own separate International Securities Identification Number (ISIN). They are classified as shares, rather than as financial derivatives, since they represent a claim on the residual value of a corporation. Issuers of shares use subscription rights to provide existing shareholders with the opportunity to participate in new issues, which enables them to retain their proportional share in the ownership of the corporation. To make the new shares even more attractive, these subscription rights may also allow existing shareholders to buy the shares at less than the market price.

NAME: Bankers acceptance
DESCRIPTION: A negotiable order to pay a specified amount of money on a future date, accepted and guaranteed by a bank and drawn on a deposit at a bank.

NAME: Other money market instrument
DESCRIPTION: A money market instrument that is of a type not listed separately.

NAME: Other Assets ABS
DESCRIPTION: An ABS that is of a type not listed separately.

NAME: Other MBS
DESCRIPTION: An MBS that is of a type not listed separately.

NAME: Other hybrid debt Instrument
DESCRIPTION: A hybrid debt instrument that is of a type not listed separately.

NAME: Convertible bond
DESCRIPTION: A fixed interest rate bond that the investor has the option of converting into the equity of the borrower or its parent.

NAME: Participating preferred share
DESCRIPTION: Holders are entitled to participate in the profits of a corporation over and above fixed dividends by means of an additional fluctuating dividend. They also participate in the distribution of the residual value of a corporation on dissolution.

NAME: Manufactured housing leases ABS
DESCRIPTION: Asset type breakdown of ABSs mainly in accordance with definitions of European and American Securitisation Forum.

NAME: Other bond
DESCRIPTION: A bond that is of a type not listed separately.

NAME: Consumer loans ABS
DESCRIPTION: Asset type breakdown of ABSs mainly in accordance with definitions of European and American Securitisation Forum.

NAME: Commercial mortgage-backed security (CMBS)
DESCRIPTION: with definitions of European and American Securitisation Forum.

NAME: Straight bond
DESCRIPTION: A bond without any further special characteristics listed separately.

NAME: Perpetual bond
DESCRIPTION: A debt security that has no stated maturity date.

NAME: Global depository receipt (GDR)
DESCRIPTION: Global depository receipts (GDR) are securities available in one or more markets outside the corporation’s country of residence.

NAME: Mixed MBS
DESCRIPTION: An MBS that is a mix of different MBS types, e.g. combination of RMBS and CMBS.

NAME: Structured debt security (Certificates)
DESCRIPTION: Structured debt securities typically combine a debt security, or a basket of debt securities, with a financial derivative, or a basket of financial derivatives. These financial derivatives are typically embedded in and are therefore inseparable from the debt securities.

NAME: Credit card receivables ABS
DESCRIPTION: Asset type breakdown of ABSs mainly in accordance with definitions of European and American Securitisation Forum.

NAME: Small and medium-sized enterprises (SME) loans ABS
DESCRIPTION: Asset type breakdown of ABSs mainly in accordance with definitions of European and American Securitisation Forum.

NAME: Cumulative, participating preferred share
DESCRIPTION: A preferred share that fulfils the criteria of cumulative and participating preferred shares at the same time.

NAME: Medium-term note
DESCRIPTION: A debt security issued at fixed or floating rates of interest, as part of an overall medium-term note programme. Used by institutions as a source for medium-term funding.

NAME: MBS - No detailed classification available
DESCRIPTION: To be reported, in case it is known that the security is a MBS, but the type is unknown.

NAME: ABS - No detailed classification available
DESCRIPTION: To be reported, in case it is known that the security is a ABS, but the type is unknown.

NAME: Non-participating (preferred) share
DESCRIPTION: Holders are entitled to receive a fixed dividend, but do not participate in the distribution of the residual value of a corporation on dissolution.

NAME: Treasury bill
DESCRIPTION: A common form of sovereign shortterm debt security that many governments issue. It gives the holder the unconditional right to receive stated fixed sums on a specified date, and is issued at a discount to face value that depends on the rate of interest and the time to maturity.

NAME: Convertible (preferred) share
DESCRIPTION: Holders are allowed to convert preferred shares into a specified amount of ordinary shares.

NAME: Bonds with warrants attached
DESCRIPTION: Bonds with warrants attached are debt securities that incorporate warrants giving the holder the option to purchase equity in the issuer or another company during a predetermined period, or at a particular date, and at a fixed contract price. The warrant may be detachable and traded separately from the debt security.

NAME: Certificate of deposit
DESCRIPTION: Usually a negotiable certificate issued by a bank acknowledging a deposit in that bank for a specified period of time at a specified interest rate.

NAME: American depository receipt (ADR)
DESCRIPTION: American depository receipts (ADR) are liabilities of the non-U.S. institutional units whose securities underlie the ADR, not of the U.S. financial institutions issuing the ADR.

NAME: Securitisation and Covered Bond - No detailed classification available
DESCRIPTION: To be reported, in case it is known that the security is a securitistion or covered bond, but the type is not known.

NAME: Other depository receipt
DESCRIPTION: A depository receipt that is of a type not listed separately.

NAME: Whole Business Securitisation (WBS) ABS
DESCRIPTION: Asset type breakdown of ABSs mainly in accordance with definitions of European and American Securitisation Forum.

NAME: Securitisation bond
DESCRIPTION: Securitisation is the issuance of debt securities for which coupon or principal payments are backed by specified assets or by future income streams.

NAME: Linked bond
DESCRIPTION: Linked bonds have their coupon or principal payments (or both) linked to a general price index for goods and services (such as the consumer price index (CPI)), interest rate (such as the London interbank offered rate (LIBOR) or a bond yield), or asset price.

NAME: Other preferred share
DESCRIPTION: A prefered share that is of a type not listed separately.

NAME: Cumulative preferred share
DESCRIPTION: Holders are entitled to receive a fixed dividend ahead of ordinary shares and retain the right to any accumulated preferred dividends that may have built up.

NAME: Home equity loans ABS
DESCRIPTION: Asset type breakdown of ABSs mainly in accordance with definitions of European and American Securitisation Forum.

NAME: Auto loans ABS
DESCRIPTION: Asset type breakdown of ABSs mainly in accordance with definitions of European and American Securitisation Forum.

NAME: Residential mortgage-backed security (RMBS)
DESCRIPTION: Detailed asset type breakdown of MBSs mainly in accordance

NAME: Strip bond
DESCRIPTION: Separate trading of registered interest and principal of securities (STRIPS) are securities that have been transformed from a principal amount and periodic coupons into a series of zero-coupon bonds, with the range of maturities matching the coupon payment dates and the redemption date of the principal amount.

NAME: Other securitisation
DESCRIPTION: A securitisation that is of a type not listed separately.

NAME: Student loans ABS
DESCRIPTION: Asset type breakdown of ABSs mainly in accordance with definitions of European and American Securitisation Forum.

NAME: Securitisation - No detailed classification available
DESCRIPTION: To be reported, in case it is known that the security is a securitisation, but the type is unknown.

NAME: Covered bond
DESCRIPTION: Covered bonds are debt securities issued by a financial corporation, or fully guaranteed by a financial corporation. In case of default of the issuing or guarantor financial corporation, bond holders have a priority claim on the cover pool, in addition to their ordinary claim on the financial corporation.

NAME: Redeemable preferred share
DESCRIPTION: These can be redeemed at the request of either the corporation or the shareholder (at a fixed price on a specified date or during a specified period of time). Strict conditions apply to the issuance of redeemable shares and their redemption. Instead of cancelling shares on redemption, a corporation may continue to hold such shares as treasury shares, but no voting rights may be exercised and no dividends are payable.

NAME: Collateralised Debt Obligation (CDO)
DESCRIPTION: A bond, created through securitisation, whose coupon payments and principal repayments are dependent on a diversified pool of loan and bond instruments, either purchased in the secondary market or from the balance sheet of an original asset owner; excluding mortgages.

NAME: Mortgage-backed security (MBS)
DESCRIPTION: A bond, created through securitisation, whose coupon payments and principal repayments are dependent on a pool of mortgages, either purchased in the secondary market or from the balance sheet of an original asset owner.

NAME: Securitisation
DESCRIPTION: Securitisation is the issuance of debt securities for which coupon or principal payments are backed by specified assets or by future income streams.

NAME: Asset-backed security (ABS)
DESCRIPTION: A bond, created through securitisation, whose coupon payments and principal repayments are dependent on a pool of assets, either purchased in the secondary market or from the balance sheet of an original asset owner; excluding mortgages.

NAME: Equipment leases ABS
DESCRIPTION: Asset type breakdown of ABSs mainly in accordance with definitions of European and American Securitisation Forum.

NAME: Mixed securitisation
DESCRIPTION: A securitisation that is a mix of different securitisation types, e.g. combination of auto loans and mortgages.

NAME: Collateralised Mortgage Obligation (CMO)
DESCRIPTION: A bond, created through securitisation, whose coupon payments and principal repayments are dependent on a diversified pool of loan and bond instruments of mortgages, either purchased in the secondary market or from the balance sheet of an original asset owner.

NAME: Mixed ABS
DESCRIPTION: An ABS that is a mix of different ABS types, e.g. combination of auto and consumer loans.

NAME: Other Covered bond
DESCRIPTION: A covered bond that is of a type not listed separately.

In case of default of the issuing or guarantor financial corporation, bond holders have a priority claim on the cover pool, in addition to their ordinary claim on the financial corporation.

NAME: Other hybrid equity instrument
DESCRIPTION: A hybrid equity instrument that is of a type not listed separately.

NAME: Participation certificate (Genussschein)
DESCRIPTION: Participation certificates grant their holders participation rights. Participation rights may take various forms, both for equity securities and for debt securities. In many countries, almost no legal restrictions are placed on this type of financial instrument. Depending on their specific features, participation certificates are considered to be either equity securities or debt securities. They are treated as equity securities if the following criteria are met: a) the holder’s claims are subordinated, b)the holder’s remuneration is performance related and c) capital is provided for an unlimited period, or at least on a long-term basis. In light of these criteria, most participation certificates are considered to be equity securities. 3.47 “Genussscheine” (or “Genussrechte”) are a type of participation certificate. These are issued mainly in European countries such as Germany, Austria, and Switzerland. “Genussscheine” sometimes have a stated maturity.

NAME: Commercial paper
DESCRIPTION: A discounted and unsecured debt security issued by a corporation whose name appears on the front of the security and who promises to pay to the security holder a certain amount on a stated maturity date.

NAME: Stapled debt instrument
DESCRIPTION: Stapled instruments - which, under their terms of issue, are two or more different financial instruments (for example, ordinary equity securities and unsecured notes) coupled together for certain purposes - are usually treated separately as fixed interest rate debt securities and equity securities. However, stapled instruments usually cannot be transferred separately either in the market or as the result of an over-the-counter (OTC) transaction. A parcel consisting of one equity security and one or more notes is traded in the market as though it were a single security, although conceptually the components are regarded as separate. If the components cannot be separately identified, the stapled instrument should be classified according to the predominant component, that is, either as a debt security or an equity security.

NAME: Other securitisation
DESCRIPTION: A securitisation that is of a type not listed separately.

NAME: Traditional securitisation
DESCRIPTION: In case of traditional securitisation, the transfer of credit risk takes place by transferring the assets subject to that risk.

NAME: Jumbo covered bond
DESCRIPTION: Jumbo covered bonds are covered bonds issued in accordance with the requirements in Article 52(4) of Directive 2009/65/EC and with an issuing volume of at least EUR 1 billion, for which at least three market-makers provide regular bid and ask quotes.

NAME: Euro commercial paper (ECP)
DESCRIPTION: A commercial paper denominated in Euro.

NAME: Other covered bond

NAME: Contingent convertible bonds (CoCo’s)
DESCRIPTION: Contingent convertible securities are hybrid securities issued as debt instruments and automatically converted into equity shares if a contractually pre-defined 'trigger event' occurs. Their defining characteristics are a loss-absorption mechanism (conversion or write-down) and an activation trigger, either based on a mechanical rule or on supervisors’ discretion.

NAME: Other MTN

NAME: Specific allowances (GAAP)
DESCRIPTION: To be used if the instrument is subject to impairment in accordance with an applied accounting standard other than IFRS 9 and specific loss allowances are raised, irrespective of whether these allowances are individually or collectively assessed (impaired).

NAME: Supervisory formula method
DESCRIPTION: Securitisations: Calculation of the risk-weighted exposure amounts for securitisation positions for which the Supervisory formula method set out in Article 262 of CRR is used.

NAME: Internal assessment approach
DESCRIPTION: Securitisations: Calculation of the risk-weighted exposure amounts for securitisation positions for which the Internal assessment approach set out in Article 259(3) and (4) of CRR is used.

NAME: IRB: Fixed risk weights
DESCRIPTION: Equity exposures: Calculation of the risk-weighted exposure amounts for equity exposures which attract a fixed risk weight treatment (without however being explicitly treated according to the Simple Risk Weight approach or the (temporary or permanent) partial use of the credit risk standardised approach) set out in Article 155 of CRR.

NAME: IRB: Simple risk weight approach
DESCRIPTION: Equity exposures: Calculation of the risk-weighted exposure amounts for equity exposures for which the Simple risk weight approach set out in Article 155(2) of CRR is used.

NAME: IRB: PD/LGD approach
DESCRIPTION: Equity exposures: Calculation of the risk-weighted exposure amounts for equity exposures for which the PD/LGD approach set out in Article 155(3) of CRR is used.

NAME: Look-through approach
DESCRIPTION: Securitisations: Calculation of the risk-weighted exposure amounts for securitisation positions for which the Look-through approach set out in Article 259(1)(e) of CRR is used.

NAME: Collectively assessed

DESCRIPTION: Securitisations: Calculation of the risk-weighted exposure amounts for securitisation positions for which the Standardised approach is used.

NAME: Credit card debt
DESCRIPTION:
Credit card debt according to Regulation (EU) 1071/2013 concerning the balance sheet of the monetary financial institutions sector,  Annex II, Part 2, Instrument categories:
"...this category comprises credit granted [...] either via delayed debit cards, i.e. cards providing convenience credit as defined below, or via credit cards, i.e. cards providing convenience credit and extended credit. .Credit card debt is recorded on dedicated card accounts and therefore not evident on current or overdraft accounts. Convenience credit is defined as the credit granted at an interest rate of 0 % in the period between the payment transactions effectuated with the card during one billing cycle and the date at which the debit balances from this specific billing cycle become due. Extended credit is defined as the credit granted after the due dates of the previous billing cycles have passed, i.e. debit amounts on the card account that have not been settled when this was first possible, for which an interest rate or tiered interest rates usually greater than 0 % are charged. Often minimum instalments per month have to be made, to at least partially repay extended credit.
The counterpart to these forms of credit is the entity liable to eventually repay the amounts outstanding in accordance with the contractual agreement, which coincides with the cardholder in the case of privately used cards, but not in the case of company cards;"

Extended credit
DESCRIPTION: Credit granted either via delayed debit cards, or via credit cards. Extended credit is defined as the credit granted after the due dates of the previous billing cycles have passed, i.e. debit amounts on the card account that have not been settled when this was first possible, for which an interest rate or tiered interest rates usually greater than 0 % are charged. Often minimum instalments per month have to be made, to at least partially repay extended credit.

NAME: Notional cash-pooling
DESCRIPTION: Cash pooling arrangement provided by an MFI (or MFIs) to a group of entities (hereinafter the “pool participants”) where: (a) the pool participants each maintain separate accounts; (b) the interest to be paid or received by the MFI is calculated on the basis of a “notional” net position of all accounts in the pool; and (c) pool participants may draw down overdrafts backed by deposits of other pool participants, without a transfer of funds between accounts. AS defined in MFS Guideline (ECB/2014/15), Glossary.

This category includes units as legal entities such as trusts, estates, agencies accounts or ‘brass plate’ companies; SPEs that qualify as institutional units and raise funds in open markets to be used by their parent corporation; units which provide financial services exclusively with own funds, or funds provided by a sponsor, to a range of clients and incur the financial risk of the debtor defaulting; special purpose government funds, usually called sovereign wealth funds, if classified as financial corporations.

NAME: Partner enterprise
Linked enterprise
DESCRIPTION:
A Linked enterprise is a Central bank and private sector company role in the sense of Commission Recommendation 2003/361/EC.

Commission Recommendation 2003/361/EC, Annex, Title I Definition of micro, small and medium-sized enterprises adopted by the commission, Article 3 Types of enterprise taken into consideration in calculating staff numbers and financial amounts:
...
3. ‘Linked enterprises’ are enterprises which have any of the following relationships with each other:
(a) an enterprise has a majority of the shareholders' or members' voting rights in another enterprise;
(b) an enterprise has the right to appoint or remove a majority of the members of the administrative, management or supervisory body of another enterprise;
(c) an enterprise has the right to exercise a dominant influence over another enterprise pursuant to a contract entered
into with that enterprise or to a provision in its memorandum or articles of association;
(d) an enterprise, which is a shareholder in or member of another enterprise, controls alone, pursuant to an agreement with other shareholders in or members of that enterprise, a majority of shareholders' or members' voting rights in that enterprise.
There is a presumption that no dominant influence exists if the investors listed in the second subparagraph of paragraph 2 are not involving themselves directly or indirectly in the management of the enterprise in question, without prejudice to their rights as stakeholders.
Enterprises having any of the relationships described in the first subparagraph through one or more other enterprises, or any one of the investors mentioned in paragraph 2, are also considered to be linked.
Enterprises which have one or other of such relationships through a natural person or group of natural persons acting jointly are also considered linked enterprises if they engage in their activity or in part of their activity in the same relevant market or in adjacent markets.
An ‘adjacent market’ is considered to be the market for a product or service situated directly upstream or downstream of the relevant market.

(a) payments in the transaction or scheme are dependent upon the performance

NAME: Insurance-linked
DESCRIPTION: Insurance-linked securitisations are securitisations where there is a transfer of insurance policies achieved either by the transfer of legal title or beneficial interest to an FVC, or there is a transfer of insurance risks from an insurance or reinsurance undertaking to an FVC which fully funds its exposure to such risks through the issuance of financing instruments, and the repayment rights of the investors in those financing instruments are subordinated to the reinsurance obligations of the FVC. See the Glossary of the ECB Guideline ECB/2014/15.

NAME: Traditional securitisation
DESCRIPTION: Securitisations involving the economic transfer of the exposures being securitised. This shall be accomplished by the transfer of ownership of the securitised exposures from the originator institution to a securitisation vehicle or through sub-participation by a securitisation vehicle. The securities issued do not represent payment obligations of the originator institution. See Article 242(10) of Regulation (EU) No 575/2013 and the Glossary of the ECB Guideline ECB/2014/15.

NAME: Life insurance policies pledged
DESCRIPTION: Life insurance policies pledged to the lending institutions in accordance with Regulation (EU) No 575/2013.

NAME: Currency and deposits in the reporting institution
DESCRIPTION: Currency and deposits in the reporting institution

NAME: Credit derivatives meeting the definition of financial guarantees, Financial guarantees other than credit derivatives
DESCRIPTION: Financial guarantees according to Regulation (EU) No 680/2014

NAME: Financial guarantee
DESCRIPTION: Financial guarantees according to Regulation (EU) No 680/2014

NAME: Equity Instruments and debt securities
DESCRIPTION: Equities and debt securities includes collateral in the form of equity instruments, including investments in subsidiaries, joint ventures and associates, as well as in the form of debt securities issued by third parties.

NAME: Protections eligible for prudential purposes
DESCRIPTION: Funded and unfunded credit protections eligible in accordance with Article 197 to 207 of Regulation (EU) No 575/2013

NAME: French
DESCRIPTION: Amortisation in which the total amount - principal plus interest - repaid in each instalment is the same.

NAME: Amortisation types other than French, German, Fixed amortisation schedule or bullet
DESCRIPTION: Other amortisation schedule applied than the ones specified.

NAME: Currency and deposits
DESCRIPTION: Currency and deposits as defined in paragraph 5.74 of Annex A to Regulation (EU) No 549/2013.

NAME: All types of risk transfer
DESCRIPTION: Member that represents all types of risk transfer (Total).

NAME: Bullet
DESCRIPTION: Amortisation in which the full principal amount is repaid in the last instalment.

NAME: Equity and investment funds shares
DESCRIPTION: Equity and investment fund shares or units as defined in paragraph 5.139 of Annex A to Regulation (EU) No 549/2013.

NAME: Credit derivatives meeting the definition of financial guarantees
DESCRIPTION: As defined in paragraph 58 (b) of Part 2 of Annex V to Implementing Regulation (EU) No 680/2014. This includes the eligible credit derivatives indicated in Article 204 of Regulation (EU) No 575/2013.

NAME: Non-subordinated debt
DESCRIPTION: The instrument is not a subordinated debt in accordance with the Table in Annex II to Regulation (EU) No 1071/2013 (ECB/2013/33).

NAME: Commercial real estate collateral
DESCRIPTION: Real estate property other than residential property, offices and commercial premises.

NAME: Movable property
DESCRIPTION: Movable property comprises pledges of physical collateral other than immovable property and include cars, airplanes, ships, industrial and mechanical equipment (machinery, mechanical and technical equipment), inventories and commodities (merchandise, finished and semi-finished products, raw materials) and other forms of movable property.

NAME: Credit default swap financial guarantee protection item
DESCRIPTION: Credit default swap financial guarantee protection item

NAME: Guarantees other than financial guarantees and credit derivatives
DESCRIPTION: Guarantees not meeting the definition of financial guarantees.

NAME: Other than Real estate, movable property, deposits, debt securities issued, equity instruments, debt securities
DESCRIPTION: Other than Real estate, movable property, deposits, debt securities issued, equity instruments, debt securities

NAME: Real estate collateral located in a member state
DESCRIPTION: Real estate collateral located in a member state

NAME: Currency and deposits in other institutions
DESCRIPTION: Currency and deposits in other institutions

NAME: Securities
DESCRIPTION: Securities as defined in paragraph 5.89 of Annex A to Regulation (EU) No 549/2013.

NAME: Loans
DESCRIPTION: Loans as defined in paragraph 5.89 of Annex A to Regulation (EU) No 549/2013.

NAME: German
DESCRIPTION: Amortisation in which the first instalment is interest-only and the remaining instalments are constant, including capital amortisation and interest.

NAME: Subordinated debt
DESCRIPTION: The instrument is a subordinated debt in accordance with the Table in Annex II to Regulation (EU) No 1071/2013 (ECB/2013/33).

NAME: Trade receivables
DESCRIPTION: Trade receivables as defined in paragraph 5.41(c) of part 2 of Annex V to Implementing Regulation (EU) No 680/2014.

NAME: Gold
DESCRIPTION: Gold in accordance with Regulation (EU) No 575/2013.

NAME: Fixed amortisation schedule
DESCRIPTION: Amortisation in which the principal amount repaid in each instalment is the same.

NAME: Credit derivatives other than financial guarantees
DESCRIPTION: As defined in paragraph 67 (d) of Part 2 of Annex V to Implementing Regulation (EU) No 680/2014. This includes the eligible credit derivatives indicated in Article 204 of Regulation (EU) No 575/2013.

NAME: Real estate collateral not located in a member state
DESCRIPTION: Real estate collateral not located in a member state

NAME: Other financial protection
DESCRIPTION: Other financial protection that is not one of the types of protection listed under ‘type of protection’.

NAME: Currency and deposits in the other institutions belonging to the banking group
DESCRIPTION: Currency and deposits in the other institutions belonging to the banking group

NAME: Other than Real estate, Deposits, Debt securities issued
DESCRIPTION: Other than Real estate, Deposits, Debt securities issued

NAME: On demand or short notice
DESCRIPTION: Instruments which are repayable on demand or at short notice at the request of the creditor.

NAME: With agreed maturity, Redeemable at notice
DESCRIPTION: Repayment right with agreed maturity or reedemable at notice

NAME: Technical null
DESCRIPTION: Technical member to represent the null value

NAME: Financial guarantees for exposures with RE Residential collateral
DESCRIPTION: Financial guarantees for exposures with RE Residential collateral

NAME: Technical null
DESCRIPTION: Technical member to represent the null value

NAME: Redeemable at notice
DESCRIPTION: Non-transferable. Without any agreed maturity which cannot be converted into currency without a period of prior notice; before the expiry the conversion into currency is not possible or possible only with a penalty. Reg EU 1071/2013

NAME: Other than on demand or short notice
DESCRIPTION: Instruments subject to repayment rights other than on demand or at short notice.

NAME: On demand or short notice, With agreed maturity, Redeemable at notice
DESCRIPTION: Repayment right with agreed maturity, reedemable at notice, or on demand and short notice

NAME: All types of risk transfer according to CRR, Article (10), (11)
DESCRIPTION: Member that represents all types of risk transfer according to CRR, Article (10), (11).

NAME: Land related to commercial real estate corporations
DESCRIPTION: Commercial real estate collateral in the form of land related to commercial real estate corporations, excluding agricultural land.

NAME: Financial guarantees for exposures with RE Commercial collateral
DESCRIPTION: Financial guarantees for exposures with RE Commercial collateral

NAME: Not secured
DESCRIPTION: The member indicates that the instrument is not secured

NAME: With agreed maturity
DESCRIPTION: Non-transferable. Which cannot be converted into currency before an agreed fixed term or that can only be converted into currency before that agreed term provided that the holder is charged some kind of penalty. Reg EU 1071/2013

NAME: All types of repayment rights
DESCRIPTION: Member that represents all types of repayment rights (Total).

NAME: Market value
DESCRIPTION: The current ‘market value’ of immovable property as defined in Article 4(1)(76) of Regulation (EU) No 575/2013. To be used if the protection is immovable property when the market value is reported in the data attribute 'Protection value'.

NAME: Non-project finance loan
DESCRIPTION: The instrument is not a project finance loan in accordance with Implementing Regulation (EU) No 680/2014.

NAME: Technical null
DESCRIPTION: Technical member to represent the null value

NAME: Fixed
DESCRIPTION: Scheme defining the interest rates during the life of the exposure which only includes constant rates - numeric constant rate known with certainty at the inception of the exposure - and where the interest rates apply to the whole exposure. The scheme may contain more than one constant interest rate to be applied at different periods during the life of the exposure (e.g. loan with a constant interest rate during the initial fixed-rate period, which then changes to a different interest rate, which is still constant, and which was known at the inception of the exposure).

NAME: Long-term sustainable value
DESCRIPTION: The ‘mortgage lending value’ of immovable property as defined in Article 4(1)(74) of Regulation (EU) No 575/2013. To be used if the protection is immovable property when the 'mortgage lending value' is reported in the data attribute 'Protection value'.

NAME: Technical null
DESCRIPTION: Technical member to represent the null value

NAME: Notional amount
DESCRIPTION: The nominal or face amount contractually agreed that is used to calculate payments in the event that the protection is executed.

NAME: Project finance loan
DESCRIPTION: The instrument is a project finance loan in accordance with Implementing Regulation (EU) No 680/2014.

NAME: Mixed
DESCRIPTION: Interest rate class other than fixed or variable.

NAME: Variable
DESCRIPTION: Scheme defining the interest rates during the life of the exposure which only includes interest rates based on the evolution of another variable (the reference variable) and where the interest rate applies to the whole exposure.

NAME: Fair value
DESCRIPTION: The price that would be received to sell an asset or paid to transfer a liability in an orderly transaction between market participants at the measurement date. To be used if the protection is not immovable property.

NAME: Types of protection values other than notional amount, market value, fair value or long-term sustainable value
DESCRIPTION: Types of protection values other than notional amount, market value, fair value or long-term sustainable value

NAME: Technical null
DESCRIPTION: Technical member to represent the null value

NAME: Technical null
DESCRIPTION: Technical member to represent the null value

NAME: Technical null
DESCRIPTION: Technical member to represent the null value

NAME: Technical null
DESCRIPTION: Technical member to represent the null value

NAME: Other type of valuation
DESCRIPTION: Other type of valuation not included in any other valuation categories.

NAME: Counterparty estimation
DESCRIPTION: Valuation method whereby the valuation is carried out by the provider of the protection.

NAME: Third-party valuation
DESCRIPTION: Valuation method in which the valuation is provided by an appraiser who is independent from the credit decision process.

NAME: Mark-to-market
DESCRIPTION: Valuation method whereby the protection value is based on unadjusted quoted prices for identical assets and liabilities in an active market.

NAME: Creditor valuation
DESCRIPTION: Valuation method whereby the valuation is carried out by the creditor: valuation undertaken by an external or staff appraiser who possesses the necessary qualifications, ability and experience to execute a valuation and who is not independent from the credit decision process.

NAME: Technical null
DESCRIPTION: Technical member to represent the null value

NAME: Observation value
DESCRIPTION:
An Observation is a field (Variable) specifying
a certain characteristic of the record (data row) identified by the Primary
key. For example, for a table containing granular information on loans, one Observation
could be the Carrying amount of that loan or the purpose of a loan (e.g.
consumption).

NAME: Complementary attribute
DESCRIPTION:
A Complementary attribute is
a field (Variable) specifying the characteristic of a specific Observation or
Dimension field. For example, for a table (Cube) containing granular
information on loans, one Complementary attribute could be the Currency of the Carrying
amount of that loan.

NAME: Dimension
DESCRIPTION:
A Dimension (of a Cube) is a field (Variable)
which is part of the Primary key. The set of dimensions in a Cube identifies
uniquely a record (data row) in that Cube. For example, for a table containing
granular information on loans, one Dimension could be the Instrument Identifier
of that loan or the Reference Date.

NAME: Dissemination
DESCRIPTION:
Dissemination Cubes are those disseminated to
the ECB business users for analytical purposes.

NAME: Staging
DESCRIPTION:
Staging Cubes are intermediate Cubes that have
been processed from the Collection ones but are still not ready to be
disseminated to the business users.

NAME: Collection
DESCRIPTION: Collection Cubes are those collected by the ECB from various sources (e.g. NCBs), normally without applying major transformations.

NAME: Feedback loop
DESCRIPTION: Feedback Loops are those used to share information between ECB and NCBs concerning what data has to be re-submitted.

NAME: Input layer to Enriched input layer phase
DESCRIPTION: The phase between the Input layer and the Enriched input layer in the BIRD process.

NAME: Enriched input layer to Reference output layer phase
DESCRIPTION: The phase between the Enriched input layer and the Reference output layer in the BIRD process.

NAME: Reference output layer to Non-reference output layer phase
DESCRIPTION: The phase between the Reference output layer and the Non-reference output layer in the BIRD process.

NAME: Writes a data set to the data base [technical]
DESCRIPTION: Writes a data set to the data base [technical]

NAME: Fetches data from the data base [technical]
DESCRIPTION: Fetches data from the data base [technical]

NAME: Generation of cubes (mostly output cubes or previous stages of output cubes)
DESCRIPTION: Generation of cubes (mostly output cubes or previous stages of output cubes)

NAME: Application of member hierarchies and aggregation
DESCRIPTION: Application of member hierarchies and aggregation

NAME: Folds variables into a variable set [technical]
DESCRIPTION: Folds variables into a variable set [technical]

NAME: Simple copy of a data set [technical]
DESCRIPTION: Simple copy of a data set [technical]
